 To convert Markdown formatted text to HTML formatted text in C++, you can use a library like `cpp-mdl` or `pandoc-cpp-api`. Here's an example using `cpp-mdl` library:

First, install the library using vcpkg:

```sh
$ vcpkg install cpp-mdl
```

Then, include the necessary headers and write the function:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <cppmark/parser.h>
#include <cppmark/renderer.h>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
  using namespace cppmark;

  // Initialize parser and renderer
  std::unique_ptr<Parser> parser(Parser::create(Parser::MARKDOWN_GFM));
  std::unique_ptr<Renderer> renderer(Renderer::create(Renderer::HTML5_ID_REUSE));

  // Parse Markdown to Ast
  Document document;
  parser->parse(document, markdown.c_str(), markdown.size());

  // Render Ast to HTML
  std::stringstream htmlStream;
  renderer->render(htmlStream, &document);

  return htmlStream.str();
}
``

Now you can use the function like this:

```cpp
int main() {
  std::string markdown = R"(
  # Hello, World!

  This is an example of Markdown formatted text.
  )";

  std::string html = markdownToHtml(markdown);
  std::cout << html << std::endl;

  return 0;
}
```

This example uses the `cpp-mdl` library to parse Markdown and generate HTML. The library is quite powerful and can handle most Markdown extensions. However, it may have some limitations compared to other Markdown processors like `pandoc`.

If you prefer a more lightweight solution, you can also consider using a simple Markdown to HTML converter library like `markdown-cpp` or `markdown-it`. These libraries may not support all Markdown extensions, but they are easier to use and have a smaller footprint.

